plastiv:
Right now plugin scans only top level dependencies, listed at the build.gradle. 
https://github.com/JakeWharton/sdk-manager-plugin/blob/master/src/main/groovy/com/jakewharton/sdkmanager/internal/PackageResolver.groovy#L272
To understand, that next library has nested child dependency
dependencies {    
    compile 'com.etsy.android.grid:library:1.0.4'
}
In general case it is required to make internet connection to the repository to download pom file, for example. 
Which means, that plugin wouldn't do local scan anymore and those numbers from the readme 
It currently takes about 100ms on average to check all of the above conditions.
may no longer be true. Yes, gradle will do this scan anyway to determine if all dependencies are present for the build and can cache already downloaded values, but do we want to do it at the plugin? May not be obvious why for the plugin users.
Proof of concept is here: https://github.com/JakeWharton/sdk-manager-plugin/pull/98
. That's a known issue already. (https://github.com/JakeWharton/sdk-manager-plugin/issues/10, https://github.com/JakeWharton/sdk-manager-plugin/issues/47)
This is due to the way gradle resolves dependency scope before any task is ever run and don't update it later.
Use next workaround:
./gradlew clean --continue
./gradlew clean assemble
. @ncalexan My best guess is that due to code
def findDependenciesWithGroup(String group) {
    def deps = []
    for (Configuration configuration : project.configurations) {
      for (Dependency dependency : configuration.dependencies) {
        if (group.equals(dependency.group)) {
          deps.add dependency
        }
      }
    }
    return deps
  }
from here https://github.com/JakeWharton/sdk-manager-plugin/blob/master/src/main/groovy/com/jakewharton/sdkmanager/internal/PackageResolver.groovy#L271-L274 
where sdk-manager-plugin scans project dependencies to find support libraries it also triggers gradle to resolve configuration. 
Because of support lib isn't downloaded yet at that point and because of gradle caches resolved configuration then project sees unresolved dependencies (even though they are downloaded).
Unfortunately, I don't see an api to skip cache and force to resolve dependencies again after downloading. https://docs.gradle.org/current/dsl/org.gradle.api.artifacts.Configuration.html#org.gradle.api.artifacts.Configuration:resolvedConfiguration
If you know how to trigger it, maybe a fix for this issue.
